# The build context is the repo root, so these patterns apply to every service
# built from it (frontend, backend).
#
# Two reasons this matters beyond image size:
#   1. Anything not excluded is uploaded to the Docker daemon on every build and
#      participates in cache keys — a stray file churns the cache.
#   2. Host artifacts must never leak into an image. A Windows-built
#      node_modules or a stale dist/ inside a Linux image fails in confusing ways.

**/node_modules
**/.git

# Build output — always produced fresh inside the build stage.
**/dist

# Secrets. The backend receives these via compose `env_file` at RUN time; they
# must never be baked into an image layer (layers are readable by anyone who
# pulls the image, and deleting a file in a later layer does not remove it).
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# Not part of any image.
loadtest
**/*.md
!README.md
